 egin{theorem}[Theorem 1: nesting and parent-corner reduction]\label{thm:parent-corner}
Under Assumptions~ef{ass:finite-var}--ef{ass:leakage-class}, the contact sets are nested:
\[
\eta_1\le\eta_2\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\mathcal Q_{\eta_1}(P)\subseteq \mathcal Q_{\eta_2}(P)\subseteq\mathcal Q_{\mathrm{LP}}(P),
\]
and therefore \(h_{\eta_1}(w;P)\le h_{\eta_2}(w;P)\le h_{\mathrm{LP}}(w;P)\) for every \(w\).  When \(\eta=0\), \(\mathcal L_0(Q)=\{0\}\) and \(\mathcal Q_0(P)\) is exactly the parent v1 independent-shock cumulant-diagonalizing SVAR/sign set.  If the LP side is restricted to the same \(\eta\)-contact set, the LP and \(\eta\)-SVAR support functions are equal for every \(w\).
\end{theorem}
 egin{proof}
Fix \(P\), \(w\), and \(\eta_1\le\eta_2\).  By Assumption~ef{ass:leakage-class}, \(\mathcal L_{\eta_1}(Q)\subseteq\mathcal L_{\eta_2}(Q)\) for every rotation \(Q\).  Hence any \(Q\in\mathcal Q_{\eta_1}(P)\) has some \(\kappa\in\mathcal K_{\delta_4}(j)\) and \(L\in\mathcal L_{\eta_1}(Q)\) with \(K_u=D(Q,\kappa)+L\).  The same witness belongs to \(\mathcal L_{\eta_2}(Q)\), so \(Q\in\mathcal Q_{\eta_2}(P)\).  This proves \(\mathcal Q_{\eta_1}(P)\subseteq\mathcal Q_{\eta_2}(P)\).  The definition of \(\mathcal Q_\eta(P)\) includes the sign-zero condition \(Q\in\mathcal Q_{\mathrm{LP}}(P)\), so \(\mathcal Q_{\eta_2}(P)\subseteq\mathcal Q_{\mathrm{LP}}(P)\).  Taking suprema of the same real-valued report \(	heta_w\) over nested feasible sets gives \(h_{\eta_1}(w;P)\le h_{\eta_2}(w;P)\le h_{\mathrm{LP}}(w;P)\), with the stated empty-set convention.  At \(\eta=0\), Assumption~ef{ass:leakage-class} gives \(\mathcal L_0(Q)=\{0\}\), so contact requires \(K_u=D(Q,\kappa)\) for an admissible separated \(\kappa\); that is precisely exact structural-basis fourth-cumulant diagonalization plus the common sign-zero restrictions.  Finally, if the LP report is itself restricted to \(\mathcal Q_\eta(P)\), both reports optimize \(	heta_w\) over the identical feasible set, so their support functions are equal for every \(w\).
\end{proof}
